---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StrategyFinder from '../components/StrategyFinder.astro';
import { calculators, absoluteUrl } from '../data/site';

const title = "Body Composition Strategy Platform — Free TDEE, BMI & Body Fat Calculators | BodyCompOS";
const description = "Learn what body composition is, why it beats tracking scale weight alone, and use our tools (TDEE, BMR, fat percentage, BMI) to construct your plan.";
const canonical = absoluteUrl();

const webAppSchema = {
	'@context': 'https://schema.org',
	'@type': 'WebApplication',
	name: 'BodyCompOS',
	applicationCategory: 'HealthApplication',
	operatingSystem: 'Web',
	url: canonical,
	description: 'A local-first body composition strategy platform for assessment, targets, forecasting, and reassessment.',
	offers: {
		'@type': 'Offer',
		price: '0',
		priceCurrency: 'USD',
	},
};

const faqEntries = [
	[
		'What is a calorie deficit and how do you calculate it?',
		'A calorie deficit (sometimes searched as calorie defecit) occurs when you consume fewer calories than your body burns to sustain life and physical activity. To calculate a calorie deficit, you first determine your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE). Eating below this maintenance level forces your body to burn stored body fat for energy. You can use a calorie deficit calculator to establish a safe deficit (typically 300–500 calories below maintenance) for sustainable weight loss.'
	],
	[
		'Can I lose fat and build muscle at the same time?',
		'Yes, this is known as body recomposition. It is highly effective for beginners, individuals returning from a training break, or those with higher body fat levels. It requires consistent resistance training, eating near maintenance calories, and consuming sufficient daily protein (1.6 to 2.2 grams per kilogram of body weight).'
	],
	[
		'Why does scale weight stall when my body shape is changing?',
		'This happens because muscle is denser than body fat. If you are gaining muscle and losing fat at similar rates, the scale weight may remain completely unchanged even as you reduce your waist size, lose inches of fat, and look noticeably leaner. Track waist measurements and progress photos rather than the scale alone.'
	],
	[
		'How to calculate FFMI (Fat-Free Mass Index)?',
		'To calculate FFMI, you need your height, weight, and body fat percentage. First, find your Lean Body Mass (LBM) in kilograms: LBM = Weight * (1 - (Body Fat % / 100)). Then calculate FFMI: FFMI = LBM / (Height in meters)^2. For individuals taller than 1.8m, normalize the score using the Kouri equation: Normalized FFMI = FFMI + 6.1 * (1.8 - Height in meters).'
	],
	[
		'How much protein do I need a day to build muscle?',
		'If you want to build muscle, scientific consensus recommends eating 1.6 to 2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight (0.73 to 1.0 gram per pound) daily. How much protein you need a day depends on your activity level and body composition. For an 80kg individual, this equates to roughly 130 to 176 grams of protein per day. Eating enough protein is critical to support muscle protein synthesis and prevent muscle loss during a calorie deficit.'
	],
	[
		'What is protein and what does it do?',
		'Protein is one of the three primary macronutrients, made up of amino acids that serve as the building blocks of human tissue. What protein does is construct, repair, and maintain skeletal muscle, organs, skin, and hormones. It also has a high thermic effect (TEF) and promotes satiety, making it the most important macronutrient for body recomposition.'
	],
	[
		'How much protein is in an egg?',
		'There are approximately 6 to 7 grams of protein in one large whole egg (approx. 50g). The protein is split between the egg white (albumen), which contains pure protein, and the yolk, which contains protein along with essential healthy fats, vitamins, and minerals.'
	],
	[
		'What is TDEE and how do I calculate it?',
		'TDEE stands for Total Daily Energy Expenditure, which represents the total number of calories your body burns in a 24-hour period. To calculate TDEE, you first find your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) using Mifflin-St Jeor or Katch-McArdle equations, then multiply it by your Activity Factor (ranging from 1.2 for sedentary to 1.9 for highly active).'
	],
	[
		'How to calculate, measure, and find body fat percentage?',
		'To calculate body fat percentage, you can use the US Navy Circumference Method, which requires measuring body fat using a tape measure around the waist and neck (and hips for females), along with height. Alternatively, you can measure body fat using skinfold calipers, bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) scales, or a DEXA scan. To lose body fat and lower your body fat percentage, you must maintain a consistent calorie deficit while eating adequate protein and doing resistance training.'
	],
	[
		'What is a healthy body fat percentage?',
		'A healthy body fat percentage varies by sex and age. For men, a healthy range is typically 10% to 20% (with 8-15% considered fit). For women, a healthy range is 20% to 30% (with 15-24% considered fit). Essential fat required for basic physiological function is 3% for men and 12% for women.'
	],
	[
		'What is my ideal weight and how do you calculate it?',
		'Your ideal weight is not a single number, but rather a healthy range. To calculate ideal body weight, formulas like Devine, Robinson, or Miller equations use height and biological sex. Alternatively, a healthy weight range is often defined as a BMI between 18.5 and 24.9.'
	],
	[
		'How to gain muscle mass fast?',
		'To gain muscle mass fast and optimize muscle hypertrophy, you must combine progressive overload resistance training (lifting weights 3-5 times a week) with a small calorie surplus (lean bulking at 5-10% above maintenance) and high protein input (1.6-2.2g/kg). Ensure you sleep 7-9 hours per night for recovery.'
	],
	[
		'What is body recomposition and how does it work?',
		'Body recomposition is the process of simultaneously building muscle and losing fat. It works by using a small calorie deficit or maintenance intake combined with high-protein nutrition and heavy resistance training. This strategy is highly effective for beginners, detrained individuals (including females), and those with higher starting body fat percentages.'
	],
	[
		'What is BMI, how do you calculate it, and is it accurate?',
		'BMI (Body Mass Index) is calculated by dividing your weight in kilograms by your height in meters squared (BMI = kg / m^2). While it is a quick population-wide screening tool, BMI is not fully accurate for muscular individuals, as it does not distinguish between fat mass and lean muscle tissue.'
	],
	[
		'What are my maintenance calories and how do I find them?',
		'Your maintenance calories are the daily calories required to maintain your current weight. To find maintenance calories, use a calculator to estimate your TDEE, then consume that number of calories for 2-3 weeks while tracking your weight daily. If your weight remains stable, you have successfully measured your maintenance calories.'
	]
];

const faqSchema = {
	'@context': 'https://schema.org',
	'@type': 'FAQPage',
	mainEntity: faqEntries.map(([q, a]) => ({
		'@type': 'Question',
		name: q,
		acceptedAnswer: {
			'@type': 'Answer',
			text: a,
		},
	})),
};
---

<Layout
	title={title}
	description={description}
	canonical={canonical}
	schema={[webAppSchema, faqSchema]}
>
	<!-- Strategy Finder Hero Widget -->
	<StrategyFinder />

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 1: What is Body Composition? -->
	<section class="site-container py-16 space-y-12">
		<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto grid gap-10 md:grid-cols-[1.2fr_0.8fr]">
			<div class="space-y-6">
				<p class="eyebrow">Topical Pillar</p>
				<h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-foreground sm:text-4xl">What is Body Composition?</h2>
				<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
					At its core, <strong>body composition</strong> defines what your body weight is actually made of. Standard scales treat every kilogram identically, but sports science separates total mass into two distinct compartments:
				</p>
				<ul class="space-y-3 text-xs text-muted-foreground list-disc pl-5 leading-relaxed">
					<li><strong>Fat Mass:</strong> All stored adipose tissue (subcutaneous and visceral fat) along with essential lipid tissues needed for hormone production and insulation.</li>
					<li><strong>Lean Body Mass (LBM):</strong> Your active tissues, including skeletal muscle, bones, vital organs, blood, and cellular water.</li>
				</ul>
				<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
					By understanding your body fat percentage and lean mass, you can select optimal metabolic strategies (fat loss cutting, lean bulking, or body recomposition) instead of chasing arbitrary numbers on a scale.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="surface border border-border p-6 rounded-2xl flex flex-col justify-between">
				<div>
					<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Why Scale Weight Deceives</h3>
					<p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2 leading-relaxed">
						Two individuals can stand at exactly 80 kg and 180 cm tall. One carries 25% body fat with minimal muscle, while the other carries 12% body fat with highly developed lean tissue. BMI classifies them identically, but their metabolic rates, health markers, and physical aesthetics are vastly different.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="mt-6">
					<a href="/calculators/body-composition-calculator" class="button-primary text-xs w-full text-center block">Calculate Your Body Comp</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 2: Platform Strategy Loop -->
	<section class="site-container py-16">
		<div class="max-w-3xl">
			<p class="eyebrow">Operating Loop</p>
			<h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-black tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-4xl">From Assessment to Reassessment</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
				Our local-first system links diagnostics, nutritional multipliers, forecasting curves, and plateau diagnostics to answer a single question: <strong>is your body composition strategy working?</strong>
			</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="mt-12 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
			{[
				['01', 'Assess Metrics', 'Enter height, weight, waist, and neck details to calculate body fat via the Navy Circumference Method.'],
				['02', 'Establish Strategy', 'Select Cut, Bulk, or Recomp based on your experience levels, current body fat ratio, and aesthetic targets.'],
				['03', 'Calorie & Protein Targets', 'Derive baseline Mifflin-St Jeor and Katch-McArdle numbers with high protein protection targets.'],
				['04', 'Weekly Check-Ins', 'Log local weigh-ins and adherence values directly to browser storage without server uploads.'],
				['05', 'Forecast Progress', 'Project completion dates and rate of change velocity using non-linear metabolic decay curves.'],
				['06', 'Correct Course', 'Identify plateaus using the Plateau Analyzer and adjust your calories dynamically to break stalls.'],
			].map(([step, title, body]) => (
				<div class="app-card flex flex-col justify-between group hover:shadow-soft">
					<div>
						<span class="text-xs font-black text-accent tracking-widest bg-accent/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded">{step}</span>
						<h3 class="mt-4 text-base font-bold text-foreground">{title}</h3>
						<p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">{body}</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			))}
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 3: Side-by-Side Comparison Tables -->
	<section class="site-container py-16 space-y-10">
		<div class="max-w-3xl">
			<p class="eyebrow">Comparison Matrices</p>
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-foreground sm:text-4xl">Scientific Strategy Comparisons</h2>
			<p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mt-2">Evaluate the exact tradeoffs between metabolic indicators and methodologies.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
			<!-- Table 1: BMI vs Body Fat -->
			<div class="surface border border-border rounded-2xl p-5 space-y-4">
				<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">BMI vs. Body Fat Percentage</h3>
				<div class="overflow-x-auto">
					<table class="w-full text-left text-[11px] border-collapse">
						<thead>
							<tr class="border-b border-border text-muted-foreground font-semibold">
								<th class="pb-2">Metric</th>
								<th class="pb-2">BMI (Body Mass Index)</th>
								<th class="pb-2">Body Fat Percentage</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody class="divide-y divide-border/40 text-muted-foreground">
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Input Data</td>
								<td class="py-2">Total weight & height only</td>
								<td class="py-2">Circumferences / LBM</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Muscle Bias</td>
								<td class="py-2 text-warning font-semibold">Penalizes muscular builds</td>
								<td class="py-2 text-success font-semibold">Rewards lean muscle tissue</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Health Utility</td>
								<td class="py-2">Population-level screening</td>
								<td class="py-2">Individual strategic targets</td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>
				<a href="/compare/bmi-vs-body-fat-percentage" class="text-xs text-accent font-bold hover:underline block pt-2">Full Index Comparison →</a>
			</div>

			<!-- Table 2: Deficit vs Recomp -->
			<div class="surface border border-border rounded-2xl p-5 space-y-4">
				<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Cutting Deficit vs. Recomposition</h3>
				<div class="overflow-x-auto">
					<table class="w-full text-left text-[11px] border-collapse">
						<thead>
							<tr class="border-b border-border text-muted-foreground font-semibold">
								<th class="pb-2">Parameter</th>
								<th class="pb-2">Calorie Deficit (Cut)</th>
								<th class="pb-2">Recomposition (Recomp)</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody class="divide-y divide-border/40 text-muted-foreground">
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Calorie Intake</td>
								<td class="py-2">15-20% below maintenance</td>
								<td class="py-2">At maintenance (or -5%)</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Velocity</td>
								<td class="py-2 text-success font-semibold">Rapid localized fat loss</td>
								<td class="py-2">Slow, gradual tissue change</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td class="py-2 font-semibold text-foreground">Protein Target</td>
								<td class="py-2">High (2.2 g/kg)</td>
								<td class="py-2">Extreme (2.2+ g/kg)</td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>
				<a href="/compare/cut-vs-recomp" class="text-xs text-accent font-bold hover:underline block pt-2">Full Strategy Comparison →</a>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 4: All Core Calculators List -->
	<section class="site-container py-16">
		<div class="flex flex-col justify-between gap-6 md:flex-row md:items-end">
			<div class="max-w-xl">
				<p class="eyebrow">Calculators</p>
				<h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-black tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-4xl">Platform Strategic Tools</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
					Access our full collection of evidence-based calculators to isolate baseline calorie targets, macronutrient partitions, and genetic muscle ceilings.
				</p>
			</div>
			<a class="button-secondary shrink-0 text-xs" href="/calculators">
				View All Calculators
				<svg class="inline-block ml-1" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
			</a>
		</div>
		
		<div class="mt-12 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
			{calculators.slice(0, 6).map((calc) => (
				<a class="app-card block group hover:shadow-soft" href={`/calculators/${calc.slug}`}>
					<div class="flex justify-between items-start">
						<p class="font-bold text-foreground group-hover:text-accent transition-colors text-sm">{calc.title}</p>
						<svg class="text-muted-foreground group-hover:text-accent transition-colors shrink-0" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
					</div>
					<p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">{calc.description}</p>
				</a>
			))}
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 4.5: Deep Dive SEO Guide (600+ Words) -->
	<section class="site-container py-16 max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">
		<div class="space-y-6">
			<p class="eyebrow">Comprehensive Guide</p>
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-foreground sm:text-4xl">The Scientific Guide to Body Composition Analysis & Metabolic Targets</h2>
			
			<div class="prose-lite text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed space-y-6">
				<p>
					To achieve your fitness goals, it is crucial to look beyond the scale. While total body weight is a simple number, a deeper <strong>body composition analysis</strong> reveals what that weight is actually made of. By definition, to <strong>define body composition</strong> is to break down your total body weight into two key compartments: <strong>lean mass vs muscle mass</strong> (incorporating bones, water, and organs) and fat mass. To understand <strong>what is body composition</strong> and the <strong>definition of body composition</strong> is to recognize that your physical fitness, metabolic rate, and health risks are dictated by these proportions, not by a single generic scale number.
				</p>
				<p>
					Many people use a commercial <strong>body composition scale</strong> or purchase the <strong>best body composition scale</strong> for home tracking. However, these tools use bioelectrical impedance (BIA) which fluctuates with hydration. For true clinical precision, a DEXA <strong>body composition scan</strong> or <strong>body composition test</strong> offers the gold standard. In the absence of an expensive scan, standard tape measurements evaluated with our US Navy equations serve as a highly reliable, zero-cost alternative. Let's explore how to calculate, interpret, and adjust these markers for your body composition.
				</p>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8">Understanding Your Body Fat Percentage & Lean Mass</h3>
				<p>
					Your <strong>body fat percentage</strong> is the proportion of total fat mass relative to your total body weight. You can use our integrated <strong>body fat percentage calculator</strong> to determine your numbers. Once you know your body fat percentage, you can compare it against the standard <strong>body fat percentage chart</strong>. For example, a <strong>healthy body fat percentage for women</strong> is typically 20% to 30%, whereas a <strong>healthy body fat percentage</strong> for men is 10% to 20%. Knowing these limits helps you establish realistic targets instead of aiming for unsustainably low percentages.
				</p>
				<p>
					If you are wondering <strong>how to calculate body fat percentage</strong>, <strong>how to measure body fat percentage</strong>, or <strong>how to find body fat percentage</strong>, the US Navy formula offers a highly validated method. It uses Waist and Neck measurements for men, adding Hip circumference for women, to approximate central adiposity. Knowing <strong>what is a healthy body fat percentage</strong>, <strong>what is my body fat percentage</strong>, and <strong>what is a good body fat percentage</strong> is the first step toward figuring out <strong>how to lower body fat percentage</strong> or <strong>how to lose body fat</strong>. In contrast to fat tissue, your <strong>lean mass</strong> includes everything else (water, organs, and skeletal muscle). By analyzing <strong>what is lean mass</strong> and separating it from body fat, you can track whether weight changes represent true muscle tissue or fluid fluctuations.
				</p>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8">Metabolic Baseline: BMR & TDEE Calculations</h3>
				<p>
					Your metabolism is powered by your resting energy expenditure. Your <strong>Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)</strong> represents the minimum number of calories your body requires to survive at complete rest. To find out <strong>what is BMR</strong>, <strong>BMR meaning</strong>, <strong>what is my BMR</strong>, or <strong>what does BMR stand for</strong> is to identify the metabolic engine of your body. Our integrated <strong>BMR calculator</strong> uses the Mifflin-St Jeor equation by default and switches to the Katch-McArdle formula when body fat is provided. This is crucial because **what is BMR in body composition** is directly linked to your active tissue mass: muscle burns more energy than fat even at rest.
				</p>
				<p>
					To calculate your total daily intake, you must understand your <strong>Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE)</strong>. To answer <strong>what is TDEE</strong> or <strong>what is my TDEE</strong> is to evaluate your BMR multiplied by your physical activity factor. If you want to know <strong>how to calculate BMR</strong>, you can use our <strong>bmr calculator for women</strong> or <strong>bmr calculator to lose weight</strong>. Once you calculate TDEE, you establish your **maintenance calories**—the daily calorie intake needed to keep your weight stable. Knowing <strong>what are my maintenance calories</strong>, <strong>how to calculate maintenance calories</strong>, and <strong>how to find maintenance calories</strong> helps you plan your nutritional phases with mathematical accuracy.
				</p>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8">Calorie Deficits & Protein Intake for Recomposition</h3>
				<p>
					To lose body fat, you must establish a <strong>calorie deficit</strong>. If you are asking <strong>what is a calorie deficit</strong>, <strong>what is calorie deficit</strong>, or <strong>what is a calorie defecit</strong>, it means consuming fewer daily calories than your TDEE. Eating in a calorie deficit forces your body to burn its own fat stores for energy. To find your optimal deficit size, you can use our **calorie deficit calculator** (or **calorie defecit calculator** / **calorie defecit calc**). A safe target is a moderate 15% to 20% deficit, which supports fat loss without compromising muscle tissue. For most adults, a **1000 calorie deficit** is too extreme, and a safer range is 300 to 500 calories below maintenance.
				</p>
				<p>
					To protect your muscles while in a deficit, you must eat enough protein. A <strong>protein calculator</strong> is essential to divide your calories into proper macronutrients. If you use a <strong>protein calculator for muscle gain</strong>, <strong>protein calculator for muscle growth</strong>, or a <strong>protein calculator to build muscle</strong>, you will find that active individuals require 1.6 to 2.2 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight. For women, a <strong>protein calculator for weight loss female</strong> ensures that calorie restrictions do not lead to muscle wasting. You can easily hit these targets by planning **calorie defecit meals** and high-protein foods; for reference, knowing **how much protein in an egg** (about 6g) helps you build a precise **calorie defecit meal plan** to hit your daily protein targets.
				</p>
				<p>
					This combination of a moderate calorie deficit and high protein intake is the foundation of **body recomposition**. If you want to know <strong>what is body recomposition</strong>, <strong>how does body recomposition work</strong>, or <strong>how to body recomposition</strong>, it is the process of building muscle while simultaneously losing fat. Many wonder: **can you build muscle in a calorie deficit**? The answer is yes, particularly for beginners or those with higher starting body fat percentages. A <strong>body recomposition calculator</strong> helps set target calorie ranges to ensure you feed muscle growth while promoting fat mobilization.
				</p>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8">Comparing BMI vs. Ideal Body Weight</h3>
				<p>
					Finally, we must distinguish between Body Mass Index (BMI) and ideal weight. To **calculate BMI** or find <strong>what is my BMI</strong>, you use the formula: `BMI = Weight (kg) / Height (m)^2`. Once computed, you compare it to a standard **bmi chart** or **bmi scale** to check if you fall into the **normal bmi** or **healthy bmi** range. While BMI is a quick population screening tool, it lacks context for muscular builds: a bodybuilder can have an "overweight" BMI despite single-digit body fat.
				</p>
				<p>
					To get a more personalized metric, use an <strong>ideal weight calculator</strong>. This tool estimates your **ideal weight** range based on your height, sex, and skeletal frame, helping you establish a healthy target. Whether you are looking for the **ideal weight for age and height**, **ideal weight for women**, or specific ranges like **ideal weight for 5'4 female** or **ideal weight for 5'2 female in kg**, our platform provides clear, evidence-based targets.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 5: F.A.Q. Accordions -->
	<section class="site-container py-16 max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">
		<div class="text-center sm:text-left">
			<p class="eyebrow">Common Questions</p>
			<h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-foreground sm:text-4xl mt-2">Body Composition FAQ</h2>
		</div>

		<div class="space-y-4">
			{faqEntries.map(([q, a]) => (
				<details class="surface border border-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden group">
					<summary class="flex justify-between items-center px-5 py-4 font-bold text-sm text-foreground cursor-pointer hover:bg-muted/10 transition-colors select-none">
						<span>{q}</span>
						<svg class="w-4 h-4 text-muted-foreground group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
					</summary>
					<div class="px-5 pb-5 pt-2 text-xs text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed border-t border-border/40">
						{a}
					</div>
				</details>
			))}
		</div>

		<div class="pt-4 text-center">
			<a href="/faq" class="button-secondary text-xs inline-flex items-center gap-1">
				View All Frequently Asked Questions
				<svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
			</a>
		</div>
	</section>

	<div class="divider-gradient"></div>

	<!-- Pillar Section 6: Trust, Privacy, and References -->
	<section class="site-container py-16">
